library("gapminder") 

country_model <- function(df) {
  lm(lifeExp ~ poly(year - median(year), 2), data = df)
}

by_country <- gapminder %>% 
  group_by(country, continent) %>% 
  nest()

by_country <- by_country %>%
  mutate(model = map(data, country_model))
## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.2.5

  mutate(
    resids = map2(data, model, add_residuals)

  1. To create the last plot (showing the data for the countries with the worst model fits), we needed two steps: we created a data frame with one row per country and then semi-joined it to the original dataset. Its possible avoid this join if we use unnest() instead of unnest(.drop = TRUE). How?
by_country <- gapminder %>% 
  group_by(country, continent) %>% 
  nest() 

country_model <- function(df) {
  lm(lifeExp ~ year, data = df)
}

models <- map(by_country$data, country_model)

by_country <- by_country %>% 
  mutate(model = map(data, country_model))

by_country <- by_country %>% 
  mutate(
    resids = map2(data, model, add_residuals)
  )

glance <- by_country %>% 
  mutate(glance = map(model, broom::glance)) %>% 
  unnest(glance) # drop unrelated columns 

bad_fit <- filter(glance, r.squared < 0.25)

gapminder %>% 
  semi_join(bad_fit, by = "country") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp, colour = country)) +
    geom_line()

bad_fit %>% 
  unnest(data) %>%
  ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp, colour = country)) +
    geom_line()
